\v 26 The sword of him that attacketh him cannot hold: the spear, the dart, nor the habergeon. 
\v 27 He esteemeth iron as straw, \add and\add* brass as rotten wood. 
\v 28 The arrow cannot make him flee: sling-stones are turned with him into stubble. 
\v 29 Darts are counted as stubble: he laugheth at the shaking of a spear. 
\v 30 Sharp stones \add are\add* under him: he spreadeth sharp pointed things upon the mire. 
\v 31 He maketh the deep to boil like a pot: he maketh the sea like a pot of ointment. 
\v 32 He maketh a path to shine after him; \add one\add* would think the deep \add to be\add* hoary. 
\v 33 Upon earth there is not his like, who is made without fear. 
